      <h2>Complete Guide to Lighting Installation in West Michigan</h2>
      <p>
        Lighting design has shifted in the last decade from a fixture-by-fixture decision into an integrated system: LED
        everywhere, smart controls on most rooms, motion and occupancy sensors handling utility spaces, and scene-based
        programming for living areas. The work that used to be "swap a fixture" now includes wiring, control selection,
        color-temperature matching, and the energy and rebate calculations that come with that.
      </p>
      <p>
        This guide covers what goes into a modern lighting project in West Michigan — residential and commercial — and
        the decisions that determine whether it looks intentional or improvised.
      </p>

      <h3>LED Retrofit vs Full Fixture Replacement</h3>
      <p>Two paths to LED in any space:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Retrofit</strong> — lamp and driver kit installed inside the existing fixture housing. Lower per-fixture
          cost and faster (5–10 fixtures per electrician-hour). Reuses cosmetically sound housings.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Full replacement</strong> — new housing, new driver, new fixture aesthetic. Higher per-fixture cost than
          retrofit, but appropriate when existing fixtures are damaged, dated, or undersized.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        See <a href="/blog/led-retrofit-vs-fixture-replacement">LED retrofit vs fixture replacement</a> for the decision
        framework, and <a href="/blog/commercial-led-retrofit-roi"
          >commercial LED retrofit ROI: payback math for West Michigan businesses</a
        > for the financial side.
      </p>

      <h3>Smart Lighting Controls</h3>
      <p>
        Smart dimmers, scene controllers, and occupancy sensors have matured past the "app-only and unreliable" stage
        into wired devices that integrate with HomeKit, Alexa, Google Home, and Matter. The biggest decisions:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Smart dimmer vs smart bulb.</strong> Dimmers win for 90% of households — one device per circuit, works
          with any LED, survives wall-switch interaction.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Neutral vs no-neutral wiring.</strong> Older homes (pre-1980) often have switch loops with no neutral.
          Lutron Caséta works without it; most other brands don't.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Occupancy vs vacancy sensors.</strong> Occupancy (auto-on, auto-off) for bathrooms and closets; vacancy
          (manual-on, auto-off) for spaces where you don't want random triggers.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        See <a href="/blog/smart-lighting-controls-explained"
          >smart lighting controls: dimmers, scenes, and occupancy sensors</a
        > for the full breakdown.
      </p>

      <h3>Outdoor and Security Lighting</h3>
      <p>
        Outdoor lighting works when it covers every approach, uses the right color temperature (3000–4000K, not 5000K+),
        is mounted 9–11 ft high at a 30° downward angle, and combines dusk-to-dawn baseline with motion triggering.
        Wiring requires <a href="/glossary/gfci">GFCI protection</a> on all outdoor circuits (NEC 210.8) and weatherproof
        in-use covers on receptacles.
      </p>
      <p>
        Several West Michigan municipalities are adopting dark-sky ordinances; full-cutoff fixtures are the right
        default regardless. See <a href="/blog/outdoor-security-lighting-guide"
          >outdoor security lighting: placement, wattage, and code</a
        > for the full design rules.
      </p>

      <h3>Commercial Lighting</h3>
      <p>
        Commercial lighting projects pair lighting design with energy code (ASHRAE 90.1 or local), rebate programs
        (Consumers Energy and DTE both run aggressive commercial LED incentives), and occupancy controls required for
        many spaces. A 5,000 sq ft retail LED retrofit typically pays back in 18–36 months when rebates are included.
      </p>
      <p>
        See <a href="/blog/commercial-led-retrofit-roi">commercial LED retrofit ROI</a> for the math, and
        <a href="/blog/commercial-electrical-maintenance-checklist"
          >annual commercial electrical maintenance checklist</a
        > for the recurring lighting checks that keep facilities efficient and code-compliant.
      </p>

      <h3>Common Lighting Mistakes</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Mismatched color temperatures.</strong> One room with 2700K, 3000K, and 4000K bulbs reads as unfinished
          work.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Wrong dimmer for the LED.</strong> Causes flickering, humming, or restricted dim range. The dimmer and
          bulb both need to be rated compatible.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Over-lit security floods.</strong> 5000K daylight floods create harsh glare that
          <em>reduces</em> visibility and irritates neighbors.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Undersized circuits.</strong> Adding 12 cans plus track plus accent lighting to one 15-amp circuit on top
          of receptacle loads. Need a load calculation.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>West Michigan Specifics</h3>
      <p>
        Holland and Saugatuck have historic-district requirements on some exterior fixtures; we work with those
        specifications when needed. Lakeshore homes often need salt-tolerant fixtures and corrosion-resistant hardware
        on the lake side. Holland Board of Public Works runs a small commercial lighting rebate; Consumers Energy and
        DTE both run significantly larger programs for businesses in their territory.
      </p>
